&ldquo;Can you please send me that file again? I cannot find it&rdquo;
&ldquo;I&rsquo;ll have to get back to you, I don&rsquo;t know where I saved the file I need.&rdquo;
I hear this every day. Even now, in 2013, more than 20 years after hierarchical file systems became the core and the norm of computing, users still struggle to understand something as simple as knowing the location of their own files in their own computer systems.

John Duns Scotus&rsquo; (1265-1308) book Ordinatio: &ldquo;Pluralitas non est ponenda sine necessitate&rdquo;, i.e., &ldquo;Plurality is not to be posited without necessity&rdquo;
William of Ockham&rsquo;s Razor, modern science version: &ldquo;The simplest solution is often the best.&rdquo;
Intentional Complexity is a manufactured situation where product configuration and operation are intentionally made difficult. It occurs when a software vendor exposes all the innards of their products to systems operators and end users.

