One of the key reasons I separated hiltmon.com and noverse.com at the start of this year was to separate my serious business voice from my larrakin personal voice.
Last evening, on twitter, it seems some of the indie celebs are doing the same:
@marcoarment @gte @gruber My only handicap is I am afraid to tarnish red-sweater with too many crazy posts, so I&rsquo;m building a new blog&hellip;
@danielpunkass, Twitter
David Barnard points out that your business should have a voice:

A woman comes across a man crawling under a street lamp. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve lost my car keys,&rdquo; he explains.
The woman tries to help the man find his keys. After a few minutes of searching, she asks &ldquo;Where exactly did you drop them?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Down the street, next to my car.&rdquo;
Puzzled, she asks &ldquo;Then why aren&rsquo;t you looking over there?&rdquo;
&ldquo;The light is better here.&rdquo;
People often look where it seems easiest or most convenient to look, rather than in a more difficult, but more correct place.

Kudos to Twitter this week for not giving in and and responding to a Subpoena for user records without notifying the users in question. Twitter, according to their privacy policy, always notifies users when they can:
&ldquo;However, to help users protect their rights, it is our policy to notify our users about law enforcement and governmental requests for their information, unless we are prevented by law from doing so.&rdquo;
Matt Graves, Twitter
